Wise Bread
Working from home

I mean the basic situation in investment banking is that if you are a
junior analyst and you are in the office fewer than like 80 hours a week,
you will be in trouble, while if you are a senior managing director and
you=E2=80=99re in the office more than like 20 hours a week you will be in =
trouble.
Analysts are expected to show up by 10ish, look busy and be available for
eight hours, order dinner, and then settle in for a long night of building
models and turning pitchbooks. If you=E2=80=99re not around and available a=
ll day,
and cranking on Excel all night, you are not doing your job.

MDs, meanwhile, are expected to get on planes and go meet with clients to
win new business. Of course sometimes they need to be in the office to
supervise and motivate their underlings, to tell them what pages they want
in the pitchbook, etc. Other times they will do client meetings by
telephone or videoconference; it happens. But in general if you are sitting
around your office all day, instead of your clients=E2=80=99 offices, you a=
re not
doing the highest-value-add part of your job.

Obviously this was upended by the pandemic. But in different ways. Analysts
lost a lot of learning and mentorship and social opportunities: Instead of
hanging out with other 23-year-olds and learning Excel shortcuts and
financial-modeling techniques and where to find the good pitchbook pages,
they had to muddle through their work on their own, which took longer and
was less satisfying. Instead of sitting in the MD=E2=80=99s office to liste=
n to
client calls, with the MD occasionally muting her line to explain what was
going on, they churned out pitchbooks alone at home. Instead of ordering
dinner to the office and joking around with their friends, they ate dinner
at home while working quietly and sadly. Sure they didn=E2=80=99t have to c=
ommute,
but their commute from Murray Hill wasn=E2=80=99t that long anyway, and the=
ir
apartments aren=E2=80=99t that nice. Perhaps they have moved back in with t=
heir
parents, which is a decidedly mixed bag.

Meanwhile the MDs, freed from the need to commute to the office, can work
from their much nicer Hamptons houses. They don=E2=80=99t need to get on pl=
anes
four times a week to meet with clients; they can just do everything from
home and then go to the beach. Perhaps they are learning less from the
serendipity and in-person interactions of being in the office, but they
were pretty far up the learning curve already. Also, remember, they just
weren=E2=80=99t in the office that much to begin with; they were always on =
planes
to meet with clients so the serendipity was limited.

Now the pandemic measures are ending and banks are going back to work. If
you are a junior banker that=E2=80=99s mostly good; you can see your friend=
s and
learn stuff and not work out of your bedroom. If you are a senior banker
that means getting back on planes and going to see clients, which is
exhausting, but also frankly if you=E2=80=99ve made it to a senior job at a=
n
investment bank that =E2=80=94 the social aspects of the job, meeting with
potential clients and trying to befriend them and understand their business
in person =E2=80=94 is probably something you enjoy. But when you get back =
from a
client trip late Tuesday night, and you=E2=80=99ve got another trip planned
Thursday morning, and the bank wants you back in the office on Wednesday to
sit at your desk =E2=80=94 *that *feels unnecessary now, doesn=E2=80=99t it=
? If you=E2=80=99ve got
a day between trips to catch up on emails and phone calls, you=E2=80=99d ra=
ther
spend it at your Hamptons house than schlepping into the office.

Anyway
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24372120.265775/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9qcG1vcmdhbi1nb2xkbWFuLWNhbGwtdGltZS1vbi13b3JrLWZ=
yb20taG9tZS10aGVpci1yaXZhbHMtYXJlLXJlYWR5LXRvLXBvdW5jZS0xMTYyNTU2MzgwMD9tb2=
Q9aHBfbGVhZF9wb3M2/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb894d3da>
:

There is a growing divide on Wall Street: firms calling employees back and
firms telling people they can work from home.

Titans like Goldman Sachs Group Inc. and JPMorgan Chase & Co. are taking a
hard-line approach, beefing up in-person staff five days a week in New York
even though it might mean losing talent. Rivals including Citigroup Inc.
are touting flexibility, betting that a softer approach will help them
poach top traders and deal makers. =E2=80=A6

Culture is at the heart of the debate. Some say the trading floor is the
last bastion of Wall Street, where interns and young employees learn by
osmosis. Others think record results in a remote-work year prove that the
trading floor and the office alike have lost their relevance.

My model is that, in the short term, more work-from-home is probably the
good trade: =E2=80=9CRecord results in a remote-work year=E2=80=9D *do *pro=
ve that you can
do it successfully for a time, using primarily bankers and traders whom
you=E2=80=99ve already trained and acculturated in the office.[2] And senio=
r
bankers and traders *will *prefer to work from their Hamptons houses, so
you can keep your senior bankers and poach your competitors=E2=80=99 if you=
=E2=80=99re more
flexible. But in the long run you want your junior bankers and traders to
be trained, at the office, by the senior bankers and traders, and it=E2=80=
=99s hard
to do that if all of the senior people are at home all the time.
Rule 29

We talked in 2019
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24372120.265775/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDMtMDUvbmVpbWFuLW1hcmN=
1cy1kb2VzLXNvbWUtY2RzLXN0dWZmLXRvbw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd9919f0b>
about a criminal case that U.S. federal prosecutors brought against former
Barclays Plc foreign-exchange trader Robert Bogucki. Bogucki=E2=80=99s team=
 did a
big FX options trade and then unwound it, and they pre-positioned for the
unwind (selling options for their own account before unwinding options for
the customer), and they sent a few intemperate chat messages about how they
would =E2=80=9Cbash the sh-t out of the market,=E2=80=9D and the prosecutor=
s decided that
was fraud. But a federal judge decided it was not fraud: Barclays had no
obligation to stay out of the market ahead of its client, there was no
expectation that this wouldn=E2=80=99t happen, etc. So the judge acquitted =
Bogucki
on a =E2=80=9CRule 29 motion,=E2=80=9D a reference to the federal rule of c=
riminal procedure
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24372120.265775/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3J1bGVzL2ZyY3JtcC9ydWxlXzI5/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBd9b13b2a>
that allows a judge to throw out a case if the government hasn=E2=80=99t pr=
esented
sufficient evidence of a crime. The judge=E2=80=99s reasoning seemed pretty=
 right
to me but I am not going to discuss it again here; you can read my 2019
post if you want more about the substance.

Instead I want to talk about this Wall Street Journal article
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24372120.265775/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9mbGF3cy1lbWVyZ2UtaW4tanVzdGljZS1kZXBhcnRtZW50LXN=
0cmF0ZWd5LWZvci1wcm9zZWN1dGluZy13YWxsLXN0cmVldC0xMTYyNTUwNjY1OD9tb2Q9aHBfbG=
VhZF9wb3MxMA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf97845f1>
about Bogucki=E2=80=99s prosecution, and in particular this part:

Mr. Bogucki filed claims against Barclays related to his suspension and
lost earnings, which the bank settled for an undisclosed sum last May. He
bought a new boat and named it =E2=80=9CRule 29.=E2=80=9D

That=E2=80=99s pretty good? Like, I don=E2=80=99t know, I guess it might be=
 a little
embarrassing to name a boat for the federal rule of criminal procedure that
kept you out of prison. Getting acquitted on a Rule 29 motion is not at all
=E2=80=9Ca technicality,=E2=80=9D it is the opposite of a technicality, it =
is a judge
finding that you are innocent and the government=E2=80=99s case is ridiculo=
us, but
still, the name does rather draw attention to that time you were charged
with a crime. But mostly I think it's great. =E2=80=9CBehind every great fo=
rtune is
a crime
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24372120.265775/aHR0cHM6Ly9x=
dW90ZWludmVzdGlnYXRvci5jb20vMjAxMy8wOS8wOS9mb3J0dW5lLWNyaW1lLw/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB6737a781>=E2=80=9D
is I suppose a reasonable theory to have at the marina. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99=
m on a boat and
not in prison due to Rule 29,=E2=80=9D you can tell your neighbor at the do=
ck;
=E2=80=9Cwhat about you?=E2=80=9D

Anyway that article is in part about Bogucki=E2=80=99s prosecution but also=
 about
the Justice Department=E2=80=99s policy of prosecuting individuals for fina=
ncial
crimes. The basic story is that after the 2008 financial crisis a lot of
banks were fined a lot of money for assorted financial misdeeds, but, like,
their chief executive officers did not go to prison. (In the U.S.,
that is; they
did in Iceland
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24372120.265775/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMTYtMDMtMzEvd2VsY29tZS10by1pY2V=
sYW5kLXdoZXJlLWJhZC1iYW5rZXJzLWdvLXRvLXByaXNvbg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfd=
e5fba7>.)
This was viewed as a missed opportunity, and so the Justice Department put
in place various policies about trying to put bankers in prison. One
particularly important one =E2=80=94 called the =E2=80=9CYates Memo
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24372120.265775/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3YvYXJjaGl2ZXMvZGFnL2ZpbGUvNzY5MDM2L2Rvd25sb2Fk/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB0fbd2fed>=E2=80=9D
=E2=80=94 said that the banks could reduce the amounts of fines they paid f=
or their
misdeeds if they helped the government put some of their bankers in prison
for those misdeeds.

This created obvious incentives: If you are a bank, and you do a bad thing,
you want to be extremely helpful to the government in pinning that bad
thing on exactly one employee. (Or a few, but one seems most efficient.)
The employee should not be too junior =E2=80=94 nobody is going to believe =
you that
some first-year analyst did the crimes =E2=80=94 but it=E2=80=99s obviously=
 not going to
be the CEO or anything; the head of a trading desk is about right. The
federal prosecutors and the bank's lawyers (who are former federal
prosecutors) will get together and decide who should go to prison for the
bad thing, and they will shake hands on it and agree that the bank will pay
a lower (or no) fine, and then they will team up to prosecute the one guy.
The bank=E2=80=99s lawyers can be very helpful to prosecutors: They have co=
mplete
access to the bank=E2=80=99s internal records, and they can interview the b=
ank's
employees in a more casual, we=E2=80=99re-all-on-the-same-team-here way tha=
n
federal prosecutors can, so they might be able to get them to talk more
freely.

If you are the one guy getting prosecuted you=E2=80=99ll feel a bit hard do=
ne by.
And so one trader who was criminally prosecuted and acquitted =E2=80=9Clate=
r sued
Citigroup Inc., his employer, arguing that the bank tried to limit its
liability by helping prosecutors build the case against him by decoding
chat-room jargon in misleading ways.=E2=80=9D Or Bogucki sued Barclays and =
has
complained that, when he was interviewed by a bunch of Barclays=E2=80=99s o=
utside
lawyers, he wasn=E2=80=99t aware that they were gathering evidence for fede=
ral
prosecutors. But they were. I guess that worked out for him =E2=80=94 now h=
e has a
boat =E2=80=94 but it does not always.
